Mosh use Interface instead of abstract class,
what is the difference?
they are both abstract concept, we can not instantiate them.
so we can build loosely coupled application (because we can't instantiate them)

we prefer an abstract class
if we want to provide some common code to all the child classes.
(we write some code on abstract class, and all the child will inheritance it)
now in this problem, we are not providing any common code to our tools
so we use Interface!

--------------------------------

using State pattern
tend our code to "Open Closed Principle" on OOP
our classes should be open for extension
closed for modification.
with "State" we can add new functionality without changing the existing code.
with if/else we need modify our code to add some functionality!
(Open Close principle means
 we don't break our old code when we our extending our code)